#  Day 99 – Career Reflection: From GRC Student to GRC Practitioner | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Day Before the Last Day

Day 98 was the course recap — the three phases of learning, the concepts that landed hardest, the real-world cases that grounded the abstractions, and what this portfolio is actually for. It looked backward at 98 days of work and tried to name what the accumulation produced.

Day 99 is different. It is the day before the last day, which makes it the right moment to look forward — not at the second-year priority agenda (that is Day 97's work) but at the larger question of what kind of GRC practitioner this journey has prepared me to be, what the honest gaps in my preparation still are, and what the transition from student to practitioner actually requires.

I want to be direct about something: completing a 100-day challenge does not make someone a senior GRC practitioner. It makes someone who has done 100 days of structured, specific, honest work on a real problem — which is genuinely more preparation than most entry-level GRC candidates have, and genuinely less experience than a hiring manager with five years in the field has accumulated. The honest self-assessment of where I stand and where the gaps are is more valuable — to me and to a future employer — than a performance of confidence that the work does not yet justify.

