## Where the Honest Gaps Are

**I have not done this work under supervision in an organizational environment.**

Everything in this project was self-directed — the risk register, the SSP, the assessment findings, the POA&M management, the AO communications. In a real organization, each of these would involve coordination with other roles: the AO's own risk tolerance and organizational priorities, the IT Administrator's competing operational demands, clinical leadership's limited availability for security process work, a legal team's input on HIPAA notification decisions, a compliance officer's institutional knowledge of past regulatory interactions.

The work I can do in isolation is preparation. The work I will learn in an organizational environment is coordination — how to get the quarterly access review completed when the Health IT Manager has three competing priorities, how to communicate a POA&M AT RISK status when the AO is skeptical of security overhead, how to maintain ISSO-IT Administrator trust when the monitoring program finds the IT Administrator's unauthorized changes for the second time.

This coordination experience is what I do not yet have, and it is what the first eighteen months in a real GRC role will primarily develop.

**I have not experienced a real security incident.**

The 2am scenario in Day 81 was designed from research, real-world case studies, and thoughtful scenario design. The IR-3 tabletop tests a simulated version of the scenario. None of this is the same as being the ISSO on the phone at 2:17am when GuardDuty fires a HIGH finding and the IT Administrator cannot reach you on the first call.

Incident response competence develops through incidents — real ones, where the documentation is not complete, the right people are not all immediately available, and the situation is ambiguous in ways that playbooks do not fully anticipate. The incident response playbooks I built are solid preparation. They are not a substitute for the experience they simulate.

**My HIPAA knowledge is strong at the Security Rule level and thinner at the Privacy Rule and Breach Notification operational depth.**

The project was scoped to the security program for a technical system — HIPAA Security Rule was the primary regulatory focus. The Privacy Rule's operational implementation (minimum necessary determinations, authorization and disclosure tracking, patient access request procedures) and the Breach Notification Rule's four-factor analysis in real investigative conditions are areas where I have conceptual grounding but not the operational depth that a compliance-side role or a privacy officer role would develop.

This gap matters for career positioning: I am well-prepared for a security-side GRC role (ISSO, GRC analyst, security compliance analyst). I am less prepared for a privacy-officer or compliance-officer role that centers on the Privacy Rule and operational disclosure management.

**I have worked on one system in one cloud environment.**

OpenMRS on AWS is a rich and genuinely complex system for a learning project. It is one system. Real GRC practitioners develop pattern recognition across many systems — on-premises environments, multi-cloud deployments, legacy systems that were never designed with modern security frameworks in mind, SaaS applications where the shared responsibility model is different from IaaS. The analytical discipline transfers. The specific knowledge of how different architectures present different control implementation challenges takes time and exposure to develop.

