## What GRC Work Actually Looks Like in Practice — What I Now Understand

The gap between how GRC is described in certification materials and how it actually functions in organizations is wide enough that naming it honestly seems useful.

**GRC in certification materials:** A structured framework of policies, controls, assessments, and monitoring that systematically reduces organizational risk to acceptable levels.

**GRC in practice:** A continuous negotiation between security requirements and organizational capacity — where the ISSO's job is to identify what the security program needs, communicate it in terms that motivate the people who control the resources and authority, and maintain accountability for the gap between what is needed and what the organization has been willing to provide.

The CP-2 AT RISK situation is the most honest illustration of this. The ISSO identified what was needed (clinical downtime procedures), completed two of four milestones (ISSO-controlled work), and then hit a wall: one unresponsive clinical leader whose attendance was required for Milestone 3. The ISSO cannot compel that attendance. The ISSO can escalate to the AO, communicate the AT RISK status, provide a draft email for the AO to send, and reduce the friction for the AO to take the needed action. What happens after that is organizational dynamics, not GRC framework application.

Most GRC work is this — doing the technical analysis correctly, communicating the conclusions clearly, and then navigating the organizational dynamics that determine whether the security program gets the resources and attention it needs. The technical analysis is learnable from frameworks and projects. The organizational navigation develops through experience.

**The ISSO is rarely the most powerful person in the room.** The ISSO has technical expertise and the authority to identify and document security gaps. The ISSO does not have budget authority, clinical authority, or the organizational standing to compel compliance from the IT Administrator or clinical leadership through anything other than persuasion, documentation, and escalation. The GRC practitioner who understands this — and develops the communication skills to navigate it — is effective. The GRC practitioner who expects technical correctness to be sufficient will be frustrated.

**Documentation is organizational memory.** The SSP, the POA&M, the monitoring log, the SAR — these are not just compliance artifacts. They are the organizational memory that allows the second ISSO to understand what the first ISSO built, allows the AO to evaluate authorization decisions over time, and allows an OCR auditor to assess whether the organization has been managing its obligations responsibly. Writing documentation for future readers — not just to satisfy the current documentation requirement — is a professional discipline that matters beyond any individual project or role.

