## The Professional Habits This Project Built

Beyond the specific GRC knowledge, 99 days of daily structured work built habits that transfer across any role:

**Documenting as you go, not after.** Every day's work was documented on the day it was completed. The SSP was updated when implementations changed, not at re-authorization. The monitoring log was updated when findings were identified, not at the quarterly report. This habit prevents the documentation debt that accumulates when organizations save documentation for compliance deadlines.

**Naming gaps honestly before someone else does.** The AU-12 finding was documented with a note to future assessors. The CP-2 AT RISK status was communicated to the AO before the deadline passed. The phishing simulation absence was named in the metrics dashboard as a gap rather than simply omitted. This habit — finding and naming your own gaps before an external auditor does — is what distinguishes a mature security program from one that is optimized for the appearance of compliance.

**Making recommendations, not just presenting options.** Every communication to a decision-maker in this project included the ISSO's recommendation — continue authorization, wait on clinical downtime invocation, the Option B risk acceptance for AU-3. Presenting options without a recommendation is abdicating the expert role. Decision-makers need guidance, not menus.

**Connecting technical work to organizational purpose.** The system description started with the patient population. The risk register rated RS-004 HIGH because of the clinical care consequences of ransomware-induced unavailability for HIV/AIDS patients on antiretroviral therapy, not just because ransomware is generically bad. This habit — always knowing why the technical work matters to the people it protects — is what makes security work feel like security work rather than compliance theater.

