## A Message to the Person Starting Day 1

You are going to spend 100 days building something that most people in GRC job postings describe having but have not actually built. That matters.

The hiring manager who looks at a resume that says "familiar with NIST RMF" and then looks at this GitHub repository is comparing a self-assessment to evidence. The self-assessment is a claim. The repository is documentation of 97 days of specific, operationally grounded work on a real system — risk register entries with operational rationale, a POA&M with milestone plans and closure records, compliance mapping with four-layer evidence chains, incident response playbooks designed to find the gap in the IRP rather than confirm that everything works.

Do not rush through the challenge to complete 100 days. Do the work specifically. When you write a risk register entry, name the specific threat, the specific asset at risk, the specific control that mitigates it, and the specific evidence that the control is working. When you write a POA&M entry, include the milestone plan, not just the target date. When you write a communication to a decision-maker, organize it around their decision, not your analysis.

The specificity is not a quality improvement. It is the entire learning mechanism. The person who has done specific work on a real system for 100 days is genuinely better prepared for GRC work than the person who has passed three certification exams. Not because certifications do not matter — they do, for interview filtering and organizational credibility — but because the operational judgment that GRC work requires develops through specific practice, not through framework familiarity.

Start. Stay specific. Be honest about gaps. The work will teach you what the frameworks cannot.

