## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The transition from student to practitioner — specifically the gap between knowing frameworks and navigating organizational dynamics — is illustrated by the career trajectory documented in the **2014 HHS Office for Civil Rights case against Concentra Health Services ($1.7 million settlement)**.

The OCR investigation found that Concentra had conducted a risk analysis that identified unencrypted laptops as a significant risk. The risk analysis was technically sound — it identified the right risk. What failed was the organizational follow-through: the risk was documented but not remediated because the operational complexity of deploying full-disk encryption across a large fleet of laptops was not prioritized against competing IT demands.

The Concentra case illustrates the practitioner challenge precisely: the analytical work (risk identification) was done correctly. The organizational work (translating identified risk into prioritized remediation action, maintaining accountability for that remediation, escalating when operational complexity caused delays) was not done with the same rigor. A GRC analyst who can do both — identify risks accurately and navigate the organizational dynamics required to get them remediated — is what the field needs and what this 100-day project has tried to prepare.

The student can identify the risk. The practitioner can get it fixed.

